{"abstract":[{"text":"You will typically extend the functionality of your Godot game by creating","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"classes that derive from one of the various Godot types and adjust the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"behavior accordingly.","type":"text"}],"seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Articles and Tutorials","anchor":"Articles-and-Tutorials","generated":true,"identifiers":["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes","doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor"]}],"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"metadata":{"role":"article","roleHeading":"Article","modules":[{"name":"SwiftGodot"}],"title":"Using Custom Types"},"sections":[],"kind":"article","variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/customtypes"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/CustomTypes","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot"]]},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"Overview","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Creating a subclass of a Godot type involves a few steps:","type":"text"}]},{"items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Subclassing an existing Godot type with the usual Swift syntax."}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Registering your type with Godot, so users can create instances of it"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"and configure it from the user interface.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Augment the type with your own custom behaviors.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Expose your properties, methods and signals to the Godot Editor.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"type":"orderedList"},{"text":"Subclassing a Godot Type","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Subclassing-a-Godot-Type"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To subclass a Godot type, you would follow the usual Swift idiom to subclass,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and annotate it with the @Godot macro, like this:","type":"text"}]},{"code":["@Godot","class MySprite: Sprite {","    var timePassed: Double = 0","","    override func _process (delta: Double) {","        time_passed += delta","    ","        var newPos = Vector2(x: Float (10 + (10 * sin(time_passed * 2.0))),","                             y: Float (10.0 + (10.0 * cos(time_passed * 1.5))))","    ","        self.position = newPos","    }","}"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"code":"@Godot","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro does a few things, it creates a default constructor that"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"follows the convention to call the parent ","type":"text"},{"code":"init()","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method and performs any"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"registrations that you might have done in your class for variables or methods.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As you will see later, the @Godot macro is applied to a class definition, and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"will scan your type for various other macros to integrate with Godot.   These","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"attributes will not work if you attempt to apply those in a Swift","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"extension-method, as the @Godot macro has no visibility into those."}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Register-Your-Type","level":2,"text":"Register Your Type"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Now we need to tell Godot about the existence of your type, to do this you need","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to call the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"register(type:)"},{"text":" method.   I like to register all my types at","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"startup, but you can do this at any time after the module has been initialized."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Your module gets initialized on a callback from Godot at different stages, this","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"is how I register my types:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["\/\/\/ This method will be invoked at different stages of the execution,","\/\/\/ in our example, we register the type when the level being used is","\/\/\/ `.scene`.","","func setupScene (level: GDExtension.InitializationLevel) {","    if level == .scene {","        register(type: SwiftSprite.self)","    }","}","","\/\/\/ This is the entry point referenced from the `.gdextension` file","\/\/\/ that you used to declare the Swift extension:","@_cdecl(\"swift_entry_point\")","public func swift_entry_point(","    interfacePtr: OpaquePointer?,","    libraryPtr: OpaquePointer?,","    extensionPtr: OpaquePointer?) -> UInt8","{","    print (\"SwiftSprite: Starting up\")","    guard let interfacePtr, let libraryPtr, let extensionPtr else {","        return 0","    }","    initializeSwiftModule(interfacePtr, libraryPtr, extensionPtr, initHook: setupScene, deInitHook: { x in })","    return 1","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"heading","text":"Defining your class behavior","level":2,"anchor":"Defining-your-class-behavior"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To make your custom type interesting, you will want to alter the default","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"behavior that Godot provides.   In Godot, this is achieved by overwriting one or","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"more of the virtual methods available in a class."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In Godot, methods that can be overwritten start with an underscore, like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"_ready"},{"type":"text","text":" for example."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"While this would not have been my choice desining the API, I find that there is"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"enough external documentation in the Godot  world, that I decided to stick to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"it.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In the example shown above, we overwrote the method "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"_process"},{"text":" which is invoked","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"continously by Godot and we use it to change the position of our sprite.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Surfacing Methods, Properties and Signals","anchor":"Surfacing-Methods-Properties-and-Signals","type":"heading","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In addition to modifying the behavior of a built-in type, you might want to","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"surface properties that would allow users to customize your type from the Godot","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"editor, or expose methods that can be invoked by users from either other"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"programming languages, like GDScript or C#, and you might want to surface","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" that your object emits that can be wired up externally.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To do this, you will be using the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Godot"},{"type":"text","text":" macro to annotate your class, like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"this:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["@Godot","class SwiftSprite: Sprite2D {","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"When you use the ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Godot","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" macro, a number of additional macros can be used inside","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"your class, like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"#signal"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"Signals.md","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":", "},{"code":"@Callable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to surface a method to"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"Godot, and "},{"code":"@Export","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"Exports.md","isActive":true},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Behind the scenes these macros use the lower-level "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ClassDB","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" API to define functions,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"properties and their values.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Overriding-Methods","type":"heading","text":"Overriding Methods","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Godot Object model does not surface a traditional object-oriented system."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Not all the methods surfaced by the Godot API can be overwritten.  The"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"SwiftGodot binding makes this explicit.   Methods that can be overwritten are","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"declared as "},{"code":"open","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", while those that can not be overwritten are declared as"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"public"},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Godot prefixes all of the overwritable methods with an underscore (we have seen"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"in this guide some examples already, like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"_process"},{"text":").","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Another important difference is that Godot does not expect your code to call the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"“super” method, in fact, those methods do nothing in SwiftGodot."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Of course, if your Swift code relies on a class hierarhcy where you do delegate"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"code to the original implementation, you should still call the base class","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"method.   For example:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","code":["@Godot ","class Base: Node2D {","    override func _ready () { ","        \/* important work *\/ ","        \/* no need to call super._ready *\/","    }","}","","class Derived: Base {","    override func _ready () {","        \/* some prep work here *\/","        \/* because we want to execute the Base._ready important work *\/","        super._ready ()","        \/* some additional work here *\/","    }","}"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"You can think of those methods that can be overwritten as hooks into Godot, but"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with an important distinction.   When you override those methods, Godot knows"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"that you overwrote them, and might take a different course of action based on it.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"Surfacing Methods","type":"heading","anchor":"Surfacing-Methods","level":3},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To surface a method, apply the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"@Callable"},{"type":"text","text":" attribute to it, this will register"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"the method with Godot.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The only limitation is that the parameters of those methods need to be one"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"of the types that Godot can surface to the rest of the engine: anything that can"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"be passed in a ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variant","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"syntax":"swift","code":["@Callable","func readyCallback (text: String) {","    print (\"readyCallback method called with value: \\(text)\")","    return nil","}"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Now your method can be invoked from the Godot editor or from scripts written in other languages."}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The functions can be any of the types that can be wrapped in a"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"Variant.md","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":" including the core Swift data types for integers and","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"floats, the Godot Object subclasses as well as ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantCollection"},{"type":"text","text":" and"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ObjectCollection","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The ","type":"text"},{"code":"@Callable","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" macro only works in your class definition, and will not work"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"on Swift class extensions.","type":"text"}]},{"text":"Surfacing Properties and Variables","level":3,"type":"heading","anchor":"Surfacing-Properties-and-Variables"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"To surface properties and variables, use the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Export"},{"text":" attribute on them.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The simplest use case works like this:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["@Godot","class Demo: Node3D {","    @Export var greeting: String = 0","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The above code surfaces a property called "},{"code":"greeting","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" to Godot of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"type string.  Strings and numbers can be edited in many interesting"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"ways in the Godot editor, and that is exposed via two optional parameters","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"to the ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Export"},{"text":" attribute: a ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropertyHint"},{"text":" and sometimes those hints","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"can take an optional string with additional confirmation information.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To learn more, read the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" page."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Signals","level":3,"anchor":"Signals","type":"heading"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Surfacing signals is covered in the "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","isActive":true},{"text":" document.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"level":2,"text":"Low-Leve Details: PropInfo","type":"heading","anchor":"Low-Leve-Details-PropInfo"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In SwiftGodot, the "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" structure is used to define argument types,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"properties and return values.  You will be exposed to these when you define"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"signal parameters.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This is only required if you do not use the various macros provided by","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"SwiftGodot.","type":"text"}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It looks like this:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"code":["let textArgument =  PropInfo(","    propertyType: .string,","    propertyName: StringName (\"myArg\"),","    className: \"SwiftSprite\",","    hint: .typeString,","    hintStr: \"\", ","    usage: .default)"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In this case, we are declaring a property of the Godot type string, and we call","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"this "},{"code":"myArg","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".  The ","type":"text"},{"code":"className","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" is the name of the class that we are defining it,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and we can provide additional hints as to how this might be used (The Godot"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"editor can provide custom UI Editors based on this information)."}]}]}],"references":{"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Framework to write Godot Game Extensions using the Swift Programming Language."}],"kind":"symbol","role":"collection","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot","title":"SwiftGodot","type":"topic"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/ClassDB":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ClassDB","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"A class information repository."}],"title":"ClassDB","type":"topic","kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"ClassDB","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"ClassDB","kind":"identifier"}],"role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/classdb"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Exports":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Exports","role":"article","title":"Exports","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/exports","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"In Godot, class members can be exported. This means their value gets saved along"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with the resource (such as the scene) they’re attached to. They will also be"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"available for editing in the property editor. Exporting is done by using the"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/RunningInEditor":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/RunningInEditor","role":"article","kind":"article","title":"Running Code in the Godot Editor","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/runningineditor","abstract":[{"text":"There are cases where you might want some of your Swift code for your extension","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"to run while it is being used in the Godot Editor."}],"type":"topic"},"Signals.md":{"identifier":"Signals.md","url":"Signals.md","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"to define signals","type":"text"}],"type":"link","title":"to define signals"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/BindingNodes":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/BindingNodes","role":"article","title":"Referencing Nodes from your Scene","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/bindingnodes","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"You will find yourself referencing nodes from a scene in your code.   In"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"GDScript, that is usually achieved by using the dollar sign and the name of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"object you want to reference."}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/PropertyHint":{"fragments":[{"text":"enum","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PropertyHint","kind":"identifier"}],"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropertyHint","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/propertyhint","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"PropertyHint"}],"abstract":[],"type":"topic","title":"PropertyHint","kind":"symbol","role":"symbol"},"Exports.md":{"titleInlineContent":[{"text":"surface properties","type":"text"}],"url":"Exports.md","type":"link","identifier":"Exports.md","title":"surface properties"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/PropInfo":{"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"PropInfo structures describe arguments to signals, and methods as well as return values from methods."}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"PropInfo","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"PropInfo","fragments":[{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PropInfo","kind":"identifier"}],"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/propinfo","role":"symbol","kind":"symbol","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/PropInfo","type":"topic"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variant":{"fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Variant","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Variant objects box various Godot Objects, you create them with one of the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"constructors, and you can retrieve the contents using the various extension"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"constructors that are declared on the various types that are wrapped.","type":"text"}],"title":"Variant","kind":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"kind":"identifier","text":"Variant"}],"type":"topic","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variant","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variant","role":"symbol"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Signals":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Signals","role":"article","title":"Signals","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/signals","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Signals in Godot are used by objects to post interesting events that are"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"taking place, and can be used by users to easily add behavior and react"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"to changes."}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Variants":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Variants","role":"article","title":"Variants","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variants","type":"topic","abstract":[{"text":"Follow up on the fundamental building block of Godot’s data types.","type":"text"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/ObjectCollection":{"title":"ObjectCollection","type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"ObjectCollection","kind":"identifier"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This represents a typed array of one of the built-in types from Godot"}],"role":"symbol","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/objectcollection","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/ObjectCollection","kind":"symbol","fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"kind":"identifier","text":"ObjectCollection"}]},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/VariantCollection":{"url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/variantcollection","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/VariantCollection","title":"VariantCollection","kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This represents a typed array of one of the built-in types from Godot"}],"fragments":[{"kind":"keyword","text":"class"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"VariantCollection","kind":"identifier"}],"type":"topic","role":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"VariantCollection","kind":"identifier"}]},"Variant.md":{"identifier":"Variant.md","url":"Variant.md","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"Variant","type":"text"}],"type":"link","title":"Variant"},"doc://SwiftGodot/documentation/SwiftGodot/Differences":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftGodot\/documentation\/SwiftGodot\/Differences","role":"article","title":"SwiftGodot API differences to GDScript","kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/swiftgodot\/differences","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"This document lists some common differences between GDSscript and SwiftGodot."}]}}}